[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'OpenSpec just passed 57,000 stars on GitHub, and it fixes the single most annoying thing about AI coding assistants. You know the problem. You describe what you want in chat, the agent confidently goes off and builds something subtly wrong, and your actual'

[00:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'requirements are buried in a scrollback you will never read again. OpenSpec adds a lightweight spec layer, so you and your agent agree on exactly what to build before a single line of code gets written. It\'s open source, it'

[00:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'needs no API keys, and the reason senior engineers actually trust it with their codebase is the genuinely clever part. Hang on for that one. So, what is it really? OpenSpec is a spec-driven'

[00:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'development framework. Instead of letting requirements live and quietly die in your chat history, you turn them into artifacts that both you and the assistant can actually follow. It\'s universal, it\'s open source, it needs no API keys and no MCP server, and it drops'

[00:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'straight into the AI tools you already use every day. Think of it as a planning layer you carry with you, no matter which coding agent you happen to be using that week. And the entire project is right here, fully open for anyone to'

[01:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'read. And people very clearly want this. OpenSpec is sitting at more than 57,000 stars, with around 4,000 forks. It\'s written almost entirely in TypeScript, and it\'s MIT licensed, so it\'s genuinely'

[01:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'free to use however you like. The latest version, 1.4.1, shipped in June. For a project that is, at its core, a workflow and a folder convention, that kind of traction tells you it\'s solving'

[01:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'a real widely felt pain, rather than inventing a brand new one to sell you. And crucially, all of that traction comes from developers choosing to adopt a workflow, not from a flashy launch or a paid ad push. Here\'s the pain,'

[01:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'concretely. Without a spec, this is how it usually goes. You type a one-line request, the agent quietly fills in a dozen assumptions you never actually made, and you don\'t find out until you\'re already reading the diff. Now,'

[01:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'multiply that across a whole feature, and across an agent that doesn\'t remember yesterday\'s conversation. The requirements were never written down anywhere durable, so nobody, human or AI, can check the finished work against'

[02:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'what you actually asked for. That precise gap is the thing Open Spec exists to close. It\'s a small, familiar annoyance that quietly burns hours across an entire team every single week. Open Spec\'s answer is a simple four-step'

[02:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'loop that runs right inside your assistant\'s chat. You start with explore, where you and the agent think through what\'s actually needed. Then propose, which generates a structured change, a proposal, a'

[02:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'technical design, and a task list, all in one tidy folder. And here\'s the part senior engineers love. That proposal is small enough to actually review in seconds, so you sign off on the intent before any real code exists. Then apply'

[02:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'implements it against the approved spec, and archive files the finished spec back into your repo. You review the plan, not just the pull request, and getting started is genuinely one command. You install the CLI from NPM, run open spec'

[02:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'in it inside your project, and it scaffolds an Open Spec folder for your specs and changes, then auto-generates the command and skill files for whatever AI tools it detects, like Claude Code and Cursor. From that moment on, the'

[03:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'slash commands simply appear inside your assistant. No accounts, no keys, no day-long config marathon. You are spec-driven in about 30 seconds. And if you upgrade the CLI later, a single Open'

[03:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'Spec update command quietly regenerates all of those tool configs for you. A few things make Open Spec feel different from the heavier spec tools that came before it. It is deliberately lightweight, minimal steps, minimal'

[03:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'process, and no rigid waterfall. It\'s brownfield first, built for modifying messy existing codebases, not just pristine new ones. It\'s change model is delta-based, so you describe only what is changing, instead of re-describing'

[03:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'your entire system every single time. And it is tool agnostic by design with no lock-in to any one vendor\'s agent. Fluid, not rigid, is basically the entire philosophy in three words. And it'

[04:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'really does go everywhere. Open Spec works with more than 20 AI coding assistants right out of the box. Claude Code, Cursor, GitHub Copilot, AWS Ciro, Windsurf, and plenty more with new ones'

[04:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'added regularly. And because the specs are just plain files sitting in your repo, that planning layer follows you from tool to tool. Switch agents next month and your accumulated specs come right along with you, fully intact.'

[04:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'That portability is a genuinely huge part of the appeal. Your plan stop being trapped inside any one vendor\'s chat window, which is exactly how it should be. So, how does this actually compare to just vibe coding it? With raw vibe'

[04:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'coding, your requirements live in chat, the agent quietly guesses at every gap, and review only happens after the code is already written, which is exactly when changing course is most expensive. With Open Spec, the requirements are'

[04:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'durable artifacts in your repo, the agent works against a spec you already approved, and you review the intent up front in seconds. One approach optimizes purely for speed to a first draft. The other optimizes for actually shipping the right thing.'

[05:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'For anything past a toy project, that second one wins. The team behind it sums the whole idea up in just four words, review intent, not just code. And once that clicks, it\'s genuinely hard to'

[05:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'unsee. We have spent years carefully reviewing pull requests line by line, while the much cheaper, much higher leverage moment to catch a mistake is before any of that code exists at all. Back when the change is still just a short,'

[05:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'readable plan that takes seconds to scan. Catching a mistake there costs you seconds. Catching that same mistake in code review can cost the rest of your afternoon. Let\'s put some hard numbers on the momentum. More than 57,000 GitHub'

[05:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'stars, support for over for different AI coding tools, and around 4,000 forks from people actively building on top of it. For a framework that ships as essentially a smart folder structure'

[05:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'plus a set of generated prompts, that is an enormous amount of adoption in a remarkably short window. And it is still climbing noticeably every single week. And the best part is just how little it costs you to actually try.'

[06:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'It\'s one npm command and one init, and there is nothing at all to sign up for. You can read the whole thing on GitHub right now, even from your phone on a break, and decide for yourself in about 5 minutes.'

[06:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'If you are already handing real work to Claude Code or Cursor, slipping a spec layer underneath them is probably the single highest leverage upgrade you can make to that workflow this month. Star it, init it, and try it. Open Spec. Agree on what to build before your agent'

[06:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
